    <text id="R151990T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Confederate General John Vaughn writes Secretary of War James Seddon in June,
                    1864, to inform him of the dire situation in the Shenandoah Valley. He says that
                    he believes Staunton cannot be held.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Hon. JAMES A. SEDDON,<lb/> Secretary of War:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1864-06-05">June 5, 1864--10 p. m. (Via Waynesborough.)</date>
                        <name type="place">Fisherville,</name><name type="location">HDQRS.,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute/>
                </opener>
                <p>I have returned to this point. Artillery and wagon trains safe. My command is
                    much scattered. The enemy is pursuing. I fear I will be forced to leave the
                    Valley. Staunton cannot be held. Crook is said to be advancing from the west,
                    some twenty miles distant. The battle was fought to-day at Piedmont. The enemy's
                    strength not less than 9,000 or 10,000 infantry, heavy force of cavalry, and
                    thirty pieces of artillery.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute/>
                    <signed>J. C. VAUGHN,<lb/> Brig.-Gen., Cmdg.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
